 </p>
<h2 id=3D"heading-breadth-first-search-time-and-space-complexity" class=3D"=
g-md-h2 gamut-tbxd0s-StyledText e8i0p5k0">Breadth-first search time and spa=
ce complexity</h2>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">The time complexity of BFS algorithm depends on the num=
ber of nodes and edges in the graph. In the worst case, BFS visits every no=
de and examines every edge once. For a graph having <code class=3D"g-md-cod=
e">V</code> vertices and <code class=3D"g-md-code">E</code> edges, the time=
 complexity is <code class=3D"g-md-code">O(V + E)</code>. This linear relat=
ionship makes BFS efficient for both sparse and dense graphs, ensuring that=
 all reachable nodes are processed systematically. </p>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">In terms of space complexity, BFS requires additional m=
emory to keep track of visited nodes and to store nodes in the queue. In th=
e worst case, the queue may contain all nodes at a given level, which can b=
e proportional to the number of vertices. Therefore, the space complexity o=
f BFS is <code class=3D"g-md-code">O(V)</code>. </p>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">In the next section, we=E2=80=99ll compare breadth-firs=
t search with another popular graph traversal algorithm, <a data-testid=3D"=
domain-agnostic-link" href=3D"https://www.codecademy.com/article/depth-firs=
t-search-conceptual" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"gamut-1r92bn9-AnchorBase e1=
4vpv2g0">depth-first search</a> (DFS). </p>
<h2 id=3D"heading-breadth-first-search-vs-depth-first-search" class=3D"g-md=
-h2 gamut-tbxd0s-StyledText e8i0p5k0">Breadth-first search vs depth-first s=
earch</h2>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">When comparing breadth-first search and depth-first sea=
rch, the main difference lies in how they explore nodes within a graph or t=
ree. BFS explores nodes level by level, while DFS dives deep into one branc=
h first. BFS uses a queue, ensuring the shortest path in unweighted graphs =
but with higher memory usage, whereas DFS uses a stack or recursion, consum=
es less memory, and doesn=E2=80=99t guarantee the shortest path. In essence=
, BFS explores broadly, while DFS dives deeply. </p>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">To learn more about the differences between breadth-fir=
st search and depth-first search, check out the <a data-testid=3D"domain-ag=
nostic-link" href=3D"https://www.codecademy.com/article/bfs-vs-dfs" target=
=3D"_blank" class=3D"gamut-1r92bn9-AnchorBase e14vpv2g0">Breadth-First Sear=
ch vs Depth-First Search: Key Differences</a> article on Codecademy. </p>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">Finally, let=E2=80=99s discover the real-world applicat=
ions of breadth-first search. </p>
<h2 id=3D"heading-real-world-applications-of-breadth-first-search" class=3D=
"g-md-h2 gamut-tbxd0s-StyledText e8i0p5k0">Real-world applications of bread=
th-first search</h2>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">The breadth-first search algorithm is widely used acros=
s various domains: </p>
<ul class=3D"g-md-ul">
<li class=3D"g-md-li"><strong class=3D"g-md-strong">Shortest path finding</=
strong>: Used in unweighted graphs like road maps or network routing. </li>
<li class=3D"g-md-li"><strong class=3D"g-md-strong">Web crawlers</strong>: =
Search engines use BFS to crawl websites level by level. </li>
<li class=3D"g-md-li"><strong class=3D"g-md-strong">Social networks</strong=
>: Helps find degrees of connection (e.g., =E2=80=9Cfriends of friends=E2=
=80=9D). </li>
<li class=3D"g-md-li"><strong class=3D"g-md-strong">AI and robotics</strong=
>: BFS aids in state-space search and pathfinding.</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">These practical applications demonstrate BFS=E2=80=99s =
versatility and reliability in problem-solving. </p>
<h2 id=3D"heading-conclusion" class=3D"g-md-h2 gamut-tbxd0s-StyledText e8i0=
p5k0">Conclusion</h2>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">In this guide, we=E2=80=99ve explored the breadth-first=
 search algorithm in detail, covering what it is, how it works, its pseudoc=
ode, and Python implementation. We also analyzed its time and space complex=
ity, compared it with depth-first search, and highlighted its practical app=
lications. </p>
<p class=3D"g-md-p">The breadth-first search algorithm is one of the most e=
ssential tools in computer science. By exploring nodes level by level using=
 a queue, BFS guarantees complete and systematic traversal. Its efficiency,=
 simplicity, and reliability make it a go-to approach for graph problems, A=
I pathfinding, and network applications. </p>
